Great question! The standard approach in .NET is to **wrap file system calls behind an interface** so you can mock them in tests.

**1. Define an abstraction:**

```csharp
public interface IFileSystem
{
    string ReadAllText(string path);
    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);
    bool DirectoryExists(string path);
}
```

**2. Implement it for production:**

```csharp
public class FileSystem : IFileSystem
{
    public string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);
    public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => File.WriteAllText(path, contents);
    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

**3. Inject it via constructor:**

```csharp
public class MyService
{
    private readonly IFileSystem _fs;
    public MyService(IFileSystem fs) => _fs = fs;

    public void Save(string path, string data)
    {
        if (!_fs.DirectoryExists(Path.GetDirectoryName(path)))
            throw new DirectoryNotFoundException();
        _fs.WriteAllText(path, data);
    }
}
```

**4. Mock in tests:**

```csharp
var mockFs = new Mock<IFileSystem>();
mockFs.Setup(f => f.DirectoryExists(It.IsAny<string>())).Returns(true);
var service = new MyService(mockFs.Object);
```

**Alternatively**, the NuGet package **`System.IO.Abstractions`** provides this exact pattern out of the box — complete with `IFileSystem`, a real implementation, and a `MockFileSystem` for testing. It saves you from maintaining the wrapper yourself.

```
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

I'd recommend `System.IO.Abstractions` if you have many I/O methods to cover; roll your own interface if you only need the three calls you mentioned.
